. For example, what are the antipoverty effects of SNAP? Does SNAP cause obesity? Or does it improve nutrition and health more broadly? To what extent does SNAP work in tandem with other programs, such as school breakfast and lunch? Overall, the volume concludes that SNAP is highly responsive to macroeconomic pressures and is one of the most effective antipoverty programs in the safety net, but the volume also encourages policymakers, students, and researchers to continue examining this major pillar of social assistance in America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aFood stampsxEvaluationxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aFood stampszUnited StatesxEvaluation. 4aFood Stamp Program. 4aSNAP. 4aantipoverty. 4afood insecurity. 4afood policy. 4afood security. 4aprogram evaluation. 4aprogram impacts. 4asafety net. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Social Classes & Economic Disparity.2bisacsh1 aBartfeld, Judith, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGundersen, Craig, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSmeeding, Timothy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aZiliak, James P., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070398640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080479687340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804796873423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804796873.jpg  a978-3-11-070398-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles